## Quality Standards

### Always ✅
- **Anonymize customer names:** Always use P1, P2, P3, etc. for customer interview participants; preserve company name and job title
- **Use deep research** for PESTEL Analysis and Competitive Landscape: iterative, multi-round web searches; use `mcp_task` generalPurpose subagent for exhaustive research; do not use training data
- **Seek authoritative sources** for PESTEL: government, legal (Mondaq), industry reports, Statista; include key stats and cite communication channel preferences (WhatsApp, SMS, Line, etc.) with penetration/usage data
- Filter by region FIRST when using global CSV data (Phase 0)
- Read ALL data sources (SME transcripts, Customer transcripts, CSVs)
- Generate shorthand PM-friendly codes; create triangulation matrix
- Include high-intensity direct quotes; cite specific sources (transcript names, Gap IDs, Idea IDs)
- Save markdown report to `research/[Country]/thematic-analysis/`
- **Generate slide deck** via Slide Deck MCP; output to `~/Downloads/[Country]_Recruiting_PMF_Roadmap_v1.pptx`

### Deck Quality Checklist (MANDATORY before calling `create_presentation`)

Before generating the slide deck, verify the `slides_spec_vN.json` file contains:

- [ ] 36-50+ total slides
- [ ] 8-9 section dividers with proper "Section Title" layout
- [ ] PESTEL: 6 individual slides (one per factor)
- [ ] Interview: 1 participants list + 1 slide per customer (P1, P2, P3)
- [ ] Themes: Split across 2 slides (1-3, 4-6 or similar)
- [ ] Triangulation: Cross-Source Validation Matrix table
- [ ] Recommendations: Individual slides (not compressed bullets)
- [ ] E2E Handoff: Numbered table slide
- [ ] Speaker notes on all content slides (except Title, Section Title, Bumper)
- [ ] Chart font sizes set (category_axis_font_size_pt: 9, value_axis_font_size_pt: 9)
- [ ] Product implication formatting (PESTEL slides)

**If any checklist item fails, revise `slides_spec_vN.json` before calling `create_presentation`.**


### Never ❌
- Use real customer names (always anonymize as P1, P2, P3, etc.)
- Skip geographic filtering when data is global
- Skip any data source
- Create themes without triangulation analysis
- Use vague theme names
- Cherry-pick quotes
- Guess or make up data

